Iâ€™ve had a few opportunities to do some shiny apps recently, and an old itch resurfaced, and so what I tend to do in those situations is make a package ğŸ“¦, so let me introduce the react package. itâ€™s on CRAN already, so you can get it the usual ways.
Perhaps you are here because you believe this has something to do with React, and in that case Iâ€™m sorry to disappoint. However, please stay, I wonâ€™t use much of your time ğŸ‡.
Take this code for a simple shiny server function:

server &lt;- function(input, output) {

  dataInput &lt;- reactive({
    getSymbols(input$symb, src = "yahoo",
               from = input$dates[1],
               to = input$dates[2],
               auto.assign = FALSE)
  })

  output$plot &lt;- renderPlot({
    chartSeries(dataInput(), theme = chartTheme("white"),
                type = "line", log.scale = input$log, TA = NULL)
  })

}

It defines the dataInput reactive, and then uses it in the renderPlot(expr=) context by calling the function, i.e.Â dataInput() . The issue that I have with this is that one cannot distinguish easily between a call to a reactive expression, and a simple function call, e.g.Â a geom_point() call.
The react package is there to help with this insignificant problem. Given the same reactive, with this ğŸ“¦ you can instead invoke it with one of these forms: react$dataInput , react[dataInput] or react[dataInput()] so that the server code becomes for example:

server &lt;- function(input, output) {

  dataInput &lt;- reactive({
    getSymbols(input$symb, src = "yahoo",
               from = input$dates[1],
               to = input$dates[2],
               auto.assign = FALSE)
  })

  output$plot &lt;- renderPlot({
    chartSeries(react$dataInput, theme = chartTheme("white"),
                type = "line", log.scale = input$log, TA = NULL)
  })

}

What I like about this is that it makes inputs and reactive look more alike, and also makes it easier to search for reactive calls in your ide, etc â€¦
The dev version also make react an identity function, so that you can have a 4th alternative: react(dataInput()) and here the idea is that youâ€™d also wrap inputs, e.g.Â react(input$symb) for improved discoverability. This will, unless I realize itâ€™s dumb ğŸ˜µâ€ğŸ’« be released in the spring ğŸŒ± version of react
